methodology: Multi-group SEM with z-tests for path coefficient differences

hypotheses_tested.description: Usage frequency moderates HB → BI (stronger for frequent users)
hypotheses_tested.interpretation: Opposite of expected: HB→BI is WEAKER for high-frequency users

hypotheses_tested.description: Voluntariness moderates SI → BI (stronger in mandated contexts)
hypotheses_tested.convergence_warning: Voluntary group SE > 1.0 indicates model instability
hypotheses_tested.interpretation: No significant moderation effect (CAUTION: unreliable due to model instability)

hypotheses_tested.description: Voluntariness moderates FC → BI (stronger in mandated contexts)
hypotheses_tested.convergence_warning: Voluntary group SE > 1.0 indicates model instability
hypotheses_tested.interpretation: No significant moderation effect (CAUTION: unreliable due to model instability)

hypotheses_tested.description: Disability moderates EE → BI (stronger for persons with disabilities)
hypotheses_tested.convergence_warning: Disability group SE=4.86 indicates severe model instability (N=69 too small for SEM)
hypotheses_tested.interpretation: UNRELIABLE: Model did not converge properly for disability group

hypotheses_tested.description: Disability moderates FC → BI (stronger for persons with disabilities)
hypotheses_tested.convergence_warning: Disability group SE=28.96 indicates severe model instability (N=69 too small for SEM)
hypotheses_tested.interpretation: UNRELIABLE: Model did not converge properly for disability group

overall_summary.key_finding: H4c shows opposite effect: HB→BI is weaker (not stronger) for high-frequency users (p<.05)
limitations: Small subgroup sizes limit statistical power (Mandated N=70, Disability N=69)
Multi-group SEM requires N≥100-200 per group for stable estimates
H4e and H4f results are unreliable due to model convergence issues
Only H4c has adequate sample sizes for reliable inference
